Red tide news: Concentrations are dropping in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota.
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, more spotty blooms have been reported from areas in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decreased concentration.
The red tide extends for about 130 miles of coastline, from Pinellas in the north to Lee County in the south.
There are spots about 10 miles outside Hillsborough County, but in a relatively small area compared to last week.
Red tide has been reported in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations were reported in and along the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, low to high concentrations in Manatee County, low to high concentrations in and along the coast of Sarasota County, low to medium concentrations in and along the coast of Charlotte County, low to high concentrations in and along the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in and along the coast of Collier County during the past week.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No reports of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida last week.
